Pakistan is reportedly close to its largest-ever defense deal with China — the purchase of the long-range HQ-19 air defense system, worth $12 bln.

The deal would mark yet another major step in Pakistan's shift away from US weaponry in favor of Chinese arms. Another notable example is the expected acquisition of Chinese J-35A fighters instead of American F-35s.

Key facts about the HQ-19 system:

 Type: Long-range anti-ballistic missile (ABM) system, often compared to the US THAAD.

 Targets: Medium-range ballistic missiles (up to 3,000 km), hypersonic glide vehicles, low-orbit satellites, aircraft, and cruise missiles.

 Interception range: ~3,000 km.

 Radar detection range: Up to 4,000 km.

 Mobility: High — all components on wheeled chassis.

 Developer: China Aerospace Science and Technology Corporation (CASC). First test launch in 1999; entered service around the mid-2010s.

 Operators: Pakistan will be the first foreign operator. In June last year, Pakistani authorities confirmed receiving China's offer to acquire the system.

